Practically speaking, I usually add what seems like a reasonable amount of solvent to dissolve it and I heat it to a boil. If it’s boiling, and everything isn’t dissolved I add a little more methanol. Repeat this until it all goes in. Remove it from the heat and let it cool slowly. You should see some nice looking crystals form.

If all of your solid goes in on the first iteration, then you can remove it and cool it. If crystals form, you did a good job. If not, you can try putting it in an ice bath. If that doesn’t work, you put it back on the hot plate and boil off some of the solvent and then let it cool. If you still don’t have crystals keep repeating this until they form.

The steps in the recrystallization of a compound are:

  1. Find a suitable solvent for the recrystallization;
  2. Dissolve the impure solid in a minimum volume of hot solvent;
  3. Remove any insoluble impurities by filtration;
  4. Slowly cool the hot solution to crystallize the desired compound from the solution;
  5. Filter the solution to isolate the purified solid compound.

Recrystallization is a purification technique used to refine solid compounds. Here’s a step-by-step guide on how to recrystallize a product from methanol:

Materials Needed

  • Impure solid product
  • Methanol (as the solvent)
  • Heat source (hot plate or Bunsen burner)
  • Glassware (flask, beakers)
  • Ice bath or cold water
  • Filter paper and funnel (for filtration)
  • Stirring rod or magnetic stirrer
  • Thermometer (optional)

Procedure

  1. Dissolve the Impure Product:
    - Place the impure solid in a clean flask or beaker.
    - Add a small amount of methanol to the flask. The amount should be just enough to dissolve the solid when heated.
    - Heat the mixture gently while stirring to dissolve the solid completely. If necessary, add more methanol in small increments until the solid is fully dissolved.
  2. Filter the Hot Solution:
    - Once the solid is dissolved, filter the hot solution through a pre-warmed filter paper to remove any insoluble impurities. This can be done using a funnel and a vacuum setup or gravity filtration.
  3. Cool the Solution:
    - Allow the filtered solution to cool slowly to room temperature. This can take some time, but it promotes the formation of larger, purer crystals.
    - For faster crystallization, you can place the flask in an ice bath after it reaches room temperature.
  4. Induce Crystallization:
    - If crystals do not form upon cooling, you can scratch the sides of the flask with a stirring rod or add a small seed crystal of the desired product to encourage crystallization.
  5. Collect the Crystals:
    - Once crystals have formed, filter the mixture again to collect the crystals. Use a funnel and filter paper to separate the crystals from the mother liquor (the remaining liquid).
  6. Wash the Crystals:
    - Wash the collected crystals with a small amount of cold methanol to remove any adhering impurities.
  7. Dry the Crystals:
    - Allow the crystals to air dry or place them in a desiccator to remove any remaining solvent.

Tips

  • The choice of solvent is critical. Methanol is a good solvent for many organic compounds, but ensure that your target compound is soluble in hot methanol and insoluble in cold methanol.
  • Always perform a small-scale recrystallization first to optimize the conditions before scaling up.
  • Monitor the temperature carefully to prevent the evaporation of methanol.

By following these steps, you should be able to effectively recrystallize your product from methanol, yielding a purer compound.

What is a good solvent for recrystalization?

For organic solutes, usually the best solvent is ethyl alcohol. Why? Well, clearly, ethyl alcohol has polar and non-polar functionality, the hydroxyl tail, and the hydrocarbyl chain. Organic solutes TEND to have some solubility in the HOT alcohol, and on cooling the solute crystallizes out… As a bonus, ethyl alcohol is cheap, smells nice, and is not too hard on your hands (tho it does sting on cuts!). The ethyl alcohol we use in the lab is often so-called industrial methylated spiritindustrial methylated spirit, i.e. ethyl alcohol denatured with a BIT of methyl alcohol added, so that you can’t drink it ….

How do I separate crystals from a solution after recrystallization?

Add the solution containing the crystals to a buchner funnel containing filter paper if you are planning to use vacuum filtration or a funnel containing filter paper if your gravity filtering it. Add the solution to the filter and allow the crystals to collect in the funnel as the solution flows into a beaker for collection. Wash and agitate the crystals to ensure that impuries are removed (use the cold solvent that was used in the recrystallisation). Pull a vacuum until the product is fairly dry (if you’re vacuum filtering) and then transfer to a watch glass to completely dry.

What are the reasons to use two solvents in recrystallization?

the first solvent used typically supports a higher solubility of the molecule you are trying to recrystallize. The second solvent supports a lower solubility of the molecule. So, you dissolve the molecule at a high concentration in the high solubility solvent and then add the low solubility solvent. When you reach the point where the molecule is not soluble in the combined solvents, it begins to crystallize out of solution.

What is the benefit of performing recrystallization to isolate a product as opposed to simply evaporating the solvent and recovering the product?

Suppose you have 95 g of product and 5 g of impurity in solution. If all you do is evaporate the solvent, the solid will contain both, i.e, 95 g product and 5 g impurity. Purity = 95%

The point of re crystallization is to purify the product. For example, you work out the conditions such that 90% of the product crystallizes out while 90% of the impurity stays in solution. Then you filter the mixture, rinse it with cold solvent, and collect a much purer product. In this case you would have 85 g product and 0.5 g impurity. Purity = 99.4%, good enough for “Breaking Bad.”

Why is methanol used in recrystallization of urea?

In general, a good recrystallization solvent will dissolve the product when warm and precipitate it when cool, and ALSO dissolve the impurities in the product and NOT precipitate them when cooled so that the product crystals are purified.

Urea is polar, as is methanol, and presumably it has the right balance of urea solubility vs. temperature (or sometimes, dilution with another solvent) to give pure crystals of urea while leaving the undesired impurities dissolved.

How does recrystallization work?

Recrystallization or partial crystallization is a technique use to separate mixtures of soluble solids. The most common example is extracting sodium chloride (NaCl) from sea water—techniques for doing this were developed in ancient times. Recrystallization takes advantage of the difference in solubilities of various compounds and the fact that the solubilities vary with temperature. If a solution is first heated to drive off excess solvent, then allowed to cool slowly, crystals of the lower solubility material will precipitate first. What is the benefit of performing recrystallization to isolate a product as opposed to simply evaporating the solvent and recovering the product?

The quickest answer is this: Evaporating all the solvent will not improve the purity. Recrystallization will generally increase purity because the impurities dissolved in the solvent are removed when you filter and isolate the crystals of the desired product.
